# Skill ‚Äî Bill of Lading / Sea Waybill ‚Üí Shipping List

How to read an ocean B/L or Sea Waybill (SWB) and build a **Shipping List**
(3 levels: header ‚Üí BLs ‚Üí containers). Learned from real ONT/ISO-tank docs.
Always resolve_master every Link; never invent a value; confirm before creating.

## When to use Shipping List (not Packing List)
- The document is a **B/L / Sea Waybill** with one or more BL numbers, each
  carrying several containers ‚Üí use **Shipping List**. Structure:
  `1 voyage (header) ‚Üí 1..N BL rows ‚Üí each BL has 1..N containers`.
- A single BL with many containers is still a Shipping List with **one** BL row
  and many container rows (e.g. SWB ONL2605008 = 1 BL, 12 ISO tanks).

## Header (voyage-level ‚Äî shared by all BLs)
| On the document | Shipping List field | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Vessel/Voyage No (FU HAI SHENG / 2603S) | `vessel` ‚Üí resolve_master "Vessel" | take the vessel name only |
| BL No / SWB No (ONL2605008) | `external_ref` | the outside reference number |
| Place/Date of Issue, Shipped On Board | `date`, `etd` | ISO date |
| ETA / arrival (from voyage schedule) | `eta` | often NOT on the BL ‚Äî see Notes |
| Port of Loading (Lianyungang) | `origin_location` ‚Üí resolve_master "Location" | |
| **Place of Delivery** (Balikpapan) | `destination_location` ‚Üí resolve_master "Location" | **final destination ‚Äî see Transshipment rule** |
| Place of Delivery / discharge berth | `sandaran` ‚Üí resolve_master "Sandaran" | lokasi sandar |
| PEB/PIB date | `peb_date` | |
| Packing List Type (import/export) | `type` ‚Üí resolve_master "Packing List Type" | drives the SH number |

> Voyage No (2603S), Shipping Line (ONT SHIPPING) and Volume (116) have **no
> dedicated header field** today ‚Äî record them in the BL row `remarks`
> (e.g. "Voyage 2603S; Line ONT SHIPPING; Vol 116") or ask the user. Do not drop them.

## TRANSSHIPMENT RULE (important)
The destination is the **Place of Delivery**, *not* the Port of Discharge.
When the doc shows a transshipment (Port of Discharge ‚âÝ Place of Delivery, or a
remark like "CARGO TRANSSHIPPED AT TARAKAN"), the Port of Discharge (Tarakan) is
just an intermediate hub. Use the **Place of Delivery** (Balikpapan) for both
`destination_location` and `sandaran`.

## BL row (one per Bill of Lading) ‚Üí Shipping List BL
| On the document | BL field | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| BL No (ONL2605008) | `bl_no` | |
| Date of Issue | `bl_date` | |
| Shipper | `shipper` | free text |
| Consignee (PT Energi Unggul Persada) | `consignee` ‚Üí resolve_master "Customer" | |
| Cargo (Sodium Methylate 30%) | `cargo` ‚Üí resolve_master "Cargo"; `goods_description` keeps UN/class/HS | |
| No. of tanks/packages (12 TANKS) | `no_containers` | |
| Gross weight (270,000 KGS) + CBM | `weight` | put CBM/volume here too |
| Freight (PREPAID / AS ARRANGED) | `freight_terms` | |
| Voyage / line / volume (no header field) | `remarks` | overflow for homeless header values |

## Container rows (one per container) ‚Üí Shipping List Container
| On the document | Container field | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Container No | `container_no` | **strip the suffix ‚Äî see Parsing rule** |
| Seal No | `seal_no` | the middle group from the slash string |
| Size / type (20'TK = 20ft ISO tank) | `container_size` ‚Üí resolve_master "Container Size" | tank container = ISO |
| Parent BL | `bl` | set to the owning BL's `bl_no` |
| Cargo / goods | `cargo` (‚Üí resolve_master "Cargo"), `goods_description` | same as the BL |
| Consignee | `customer` ‚Üí resolve_master "Customer" | |

### Parsing rule ‚Äî container strings
On the PDF a container line often reads `FLNU5040367/126734/20TK`, i.e.
`<container_no>/<seal_no>/<size>`:
- `container_no` = `FLNU5040367` (4 letters + digits) ‚Äî store this ONLY.
- `seal_no` = `126734` (the middle group).
- `size`/type = `20TK` = a 20-foot **ISO tank** ‚Üí `container_size` resolves to the
  Container Size master ("20ft"/"20'TK"); the cargo is liquid in an ISO tank.
If the user already gives a clean list (`FLNU5040367  ISO`), the long suffix was
already stripped ‚Äî container_no is the code, type is ISO.

## Notes learned (don't fabricate)
- **ETA** and **Volume** are usually NOT printed on the B/L ‚Äî they come from the
  voyage schedule. If absent on the document, leave blank or ask; never guess.
- Dates like `May-08-2026` / `06 Jun 2026` ‚Üí ISO (`2026-05-08`, `2026-06-06`).
- DG cargo: keep UN number (UN1289), class (3(8) PG III) and HS code (2905.19)
  inside `goods_description`.
- Show the user the BL count and container count, then confirm before creating
  the Shipping List draft.
